  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and principles for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Frameworks\n- Countries are encouraged to align national legislation with international standards\n- Criminalization of money laundering across jurisdictions\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n3. Information Sharing\n- Cross-border cooperation between financial intelligence units\n- Mechanisms for exchanging intelligence about suspicious financial transactions\n- Collaborative investigations and prosecutions\n\n4. Compliance and Enforcement\n- International monitoring of national anti-money laundering efforts\n- Potential sanctions for non-compliant countries\n- Peer review processes\n- Blacklisting of jurisdictions with weak regulatory frameworks\n\n5. Banking and Financial Regulations\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Mandatory transaction reporting\n- Due diligence standards\n- Consistent identification and verification protocols\n\nThese intersections create a complex multilayered approach to preventing and detecting money laundering globally.",
